31/03/2006
(Various sources - 24/03/06 - 31/03/06)
Turkey's leading industrial conglomerate, Koc Holding, has joined the UN Global Compact initiative, aimed at promoting ethical business practices. 
Marking the occasion, Koc Holding chairman Mustafa V. 
Koc met with UN Secretary General Kofi Annan, who launched the initiative in 2000.
***
The World Bank has asked the Albanian government to step up efforts to improve the peformance of the national power utility KESH's financial performance. 
The call came during a visit to Tirana by bank representatives last week. 
Albania has suffered a spate of problems with power supply and the collection rate of electricity bills has dropped sharply in recent months.
***
The Serbian government and the EBRD sealed an equity investment agreement for Komercijalna Banka. 
Under the deal, EBRD will acquire a minority 25 per cent stake in the Serbian bank for 70m euros. 
It will also provide a 30m-euro loan to Komercijalna Banka for support of mortgage services.
***
Equest Balkan Properties, a Western European private investment fund, has acquired a new downtown mall, Sofia City Centre, in Bulgaria's capital. 
The 94m-euro deal is one of the largest real estate purchases made by a foreign investor in the Balkan country so far.
***
Macedonia's industrial output fell by 2.2 per cent year-on-year in February, according to the latest official data. 
Compared to the previous month, industrial production registered a 6.9 per cent increase in February.
***
Foreign Direct Investments (FDI) in Romania reached 699m euros in January 2006, up 199 per cent year-on-year, according to preliminary data from the central bank. 
FDI totalled 5.2 billion euros in 2005, and the Romanian government forecasts between 5.8 billion and 6.2 billion for this year
***
The registered unemployment rate in the Federation of BiH (FBiH) rose from 47.3 per cent in December 2005, to 47.5 per cent in January 2006, according to the FBiH employment bureau. 
In the first month of this year, the number of jobless people increased by 1,659 people to 349,137.
***
Croatia's GDP growth accelerated from 3.8 per cent year-on-year in 2004 to 4.3 per cent in 2005, according to preliminary data from the state statistical bureau. 
According to Finance Minister Ivan Suker, economic growth is expected to remain strong in the first quarter of 2006 as well.
***
The Greek government OK'd a new bill on renewable energy sources, aimed at updating the framework for electricity generation and accelerate licensing procedures in the field. 
According to Development Minister Dimitris Sioufas, the cabinet plans also to introduce tax incentives for using power from renewable energy sources.
